[89]  Korrektur einiger Fehler des IPC-Pakets
      20-Mar-1990 / Manfred Jeusfeld (UPA)

Der Einfachkeit halber fuege ich die E-Mails ein, und zwar zunaechst meine
Anfrage und dann die Antwort von Dani de Ridder (BIM).

Dear Dani,

after a quite long time I need your help again. The problem is
a bit tricky since it has to do with "inter process communication" IPC.

As you (may) know you provide the files
   Bprolog/lib/ipc.c       {C interface to UNIX BSD IPC}
   Bprolog/lib/ipc.pro     {C procedures as Prolog predicates}
   Bprolog/lib/server.pro  {Example program that accepts calls via IPC}
   Bprolog/lib/client.pro  {Example program that sends calls via IPC}

We use this for connecting a SunView-based user interface (written in
BIM-Prolog) to a knowledge base server (also written in BIM-Prolog).

Communication is done by adaptions of server.pro and client.pro.

Now, the problems are:



[#1] User interaction influences 'select' function
==================================================

If the server is resolving a goal of the client
(==> the client waits for response) and if we do some interaction on
the screen (open and iconize an arbitrary textedit window) then we get
the error message:

    IPC Error : Select failed.   {generated by ipc.c}


Additionally, the client's wait loop generates

    Server not responding. Still trying.

though the timeout isnt't due. If we continue working that style (sending
requests to the server & working simultaneously on the textedit window), we
finally (after dozens of "IPC Error : Select failed") the message

    ***SIGNAL***  SIGSEGV

for the client. That means that the client process is killed!!! That's
bad. I've looked trogh your code and found the function

    select_input_0( rfds , sfds ) in ipc.c.

It takes a set rfds (represented as an integer bitmap) of filedescriptors
and returns in sfds those which are ready for "read" operation. If the
called 'select' function has an error then the above IPC error message
is generated.

Can you give an advice??


[#2] Unregistering a client does not free the file used file descriptor
=======================================================================

The first registration of a client to the server yields the following
actions in the server:

         * Adding fd 5              {number of the new fd for the client}
         * ===> new fd set = 32     {5 is member of our fd set (2^5=32) }
         54                         {the number of free file descriptors}
         * Removing fd 5            {unregistering ...}
         * ===> new fd set = 0
         * Adding fd 6              {a new client, gets fd 6 though 5   }
         * ===> new fd set = 64     {fd 5 should be free}

Therefore, we can only have a limited number of registrations during one
session. That's bad, too! Any explanations??


[#3] Crashed client hangs up poor server
========================================

If the client crashes (i.e. terminates without unregistering from the server)
then the server crazily goes into an infinite loop printing from time
to time

          *** Start garbage collection of dynamic code ***
              Code zone usage :  91%  ( 24% static + 66% dynamic )
              Code zone usage :  44%  ( 24% static + 20% dynamic )
          *** End garbage collection of dynamic code ***

Any hint??


Thank you for your efforts. Hope the questions are simple enough and
that I provided the necessary information.

Best regards (-:

.-- Manfred Jeusfeld (University of Passau)

*******************************************************

Dear Manfred,

1) Select Failed , SIGSEGV
Currently, no solution is found .
We were able to reproduce it with a frame+panel using notify_do_dispatch.
We got the Select Failed on all machines we tested on, but :
this only gave SIGSEGV on a sun3/4.0, not on a sun4/4.0 nor on a sun3/3.5,
we have the impression that the error occurs somewhere in SunView.
We will look into this a little further.

2) the FD's
The definition of solve_goal/3 is adapted.
solve_goal( stop , _fd , _out ) :- !,
   report( 'Unregistering client.' ),
   client_db_unregister( _fd ),
   shutdown_service(_fd),               <<<<< ADDED
   write( _out , fail ), write( _out , ' .\n' ), flush( _out ) .

solve_goal( _goal , _fd , _out ) :-
   call( _goal ),
   report( 'Answer '(_goal) ),
   please( writequotes , on ), write( _out , _goal ),
   please( writequotes , off ), write( _out , ' .\n' ), flush( _out ),
   fail .

solve_goal( _goal , _fd , _out ) :-
   write( _out , fail ), write( _out , ' .\n' ), flush( _out ) .

This change solves the problem of unregistering clients without freeing the
corresponding file descriptor. In fact, the file descriptor was fysically
freed but the internal database was not updated.

3) Hanging after a crash
Definition of serve_goal/1 (in server.pro) has been adapted. A second
definiton is added in case the read fails. Then the file descriptor is closed.
In fact, there must be no input on a file descriptor of a process that hangs
or has died. But closing the corresponding file descriptor is a way of avoiding
this hanging of the server.

serve_goal( _fd ) :-
   client_db_files( _fd , _inp , _out ),
   read( _inp , _goal ), ! ,
   report( Solving(_goal) ),
   solve_goal( _goal , _fd , _out ) .

serve_goal( _fd ) :-
   report( 'Client hanging --- shutting it down' ),
   client_db_unregister( _fd ),
   shutdown_service( _fd ).

4) Garbage collection code
Definition of accept_request/1 :
accept_request( _servid , _fd , _inp , _out ) :-
   accept_request( _ret , _servid , _fd , _inp , _out ),
   {update( accept_request_status(_ret) ),} _ret = 0 .

Comment out the update. This update is added to be able to check if something
went wrong, but it also generates garbage on the dynamic code table. This
update is not necessary and can be deleted.

>> Diese Aenderung wurde in ../Bprolog/lib/ipc.pro vorgenommen

The predicate client_shutdown/1 (in client.pro) has been adapted.
client_shutdown( _serv_id ) :-
   service_db_files( _serv_id , _inp , _out ), !,
   initialize_call( _inp ),
   send_request( _serv_id , _out , stop ), !,
   receive_init( _inp ).

>> Wir haben schon seit jeher schon nicht auf Antwort nach dem
>> 'stop' gewartet. Insofern ist das 'receive_init' unverstaendlich.
>> Siehe IpcChannelAccess.pro.

When the client is shut down, no solution will be reported to it anymore.


We hope that these answers will already help you. Please don't hesitate
to contact us again when you have problems or questions with the ipc
example interface.

Kind Regards,

The BIM_Prolog Customer Support Team

***************************************************************

Anmerkungen (21-Mar-1990/MJf):

In IpcChannelAccess habe ich keine Aenderung vorgenommen (s.a. Kommentar
zu client_shutdown in client.pro). Die beiden grossen Aenderungen wurden in
IpcChannel vorgenommen:
   1) 'shutdown_service(_fd),' in 'solve_goal' einfuegen, damit beim
      Ausloggen eines Clients der Filedesciptor auch freigegeben wird.
   2) 2. Klause fuer serve_goal, damit beim unvorhergesehenen Tod eines
      Klienten (d.h. Datei _inp ist unleserlich) dieser aus der Tabelle
      des Servers entfernt wird.

Die Aenderung 2 betrifft nicht die Tabelle der eingeschalteten Tools,
die von CBserverInterface durch ENROLL_ME und CANCEL_ME verwaltet wird,
sondern (leider) nur die interne Tabelle von IpcChannel (client_db_files).
Der Grund liegt daran, dass an der betreffenden Stelle der ID des
gestorbenen Clients nicht verfuegbar ist.

Dies sollte spaeter einmal so umprogrammiert werden, dass man die
noetige Information (_fd,_inp,_out, _toolid etc) zusammen abspeichert.


