[127] Erweiterungen im Anfrageuebersetzter
      05-07-1991, Andre Klemann (UPA)

      Betroffene Module :

      - QueryCompiler.pro
      - LTassertionSimplifier.pro
      - Literals.pro
      - CBSYSASSTIME.prop

Hier der etwas modifizierte Kommentar aus QueryCompiler.pro :


* Now, also special built-in queries are considered by the  query  compiler. For
* this, the system model for query classes is extended as follows :
*
*   Class Function isA BuiltinQueryClass with
*   end Function
*
* In the following the term "function" is used to refere to an instance  of  the
* class Function. A function f is defined by the following frame  ( only parame-
* ter attributes are considered ) :
*
*  Function f isA <primitive class> with
*     parameter
*       p1 : C1;
*       ...
*       pn : Cn
*  end f
*
* The superclass <primitive class> must be a primitive class, i.e. Integer,Real,
* or String or specializations of them. For each such function there is  a  pre-
* dicate with clause head process_f(_this,_p1,...,_pn) defined in the ".builtin"
* file of the application. When loading the  (existing)  application  file  this
* predicate is defined global. Functions may only be used  in  combination  with
* derive expressions in an InstanceOf literal in a query rule of  another  query
* to instanciate the arguments of the pedicate, e.g.
*
*                  InstanceOf(return_val,f([v1/p1,...,vn/pn])).
*
* The query compiler replaces this literal in the PL-tree of the query with  the
* literal
*
*                       process_f(return_val,v1,...,vn)
*
* ( see resolve_derive_expression/2 replace_derive_expression/3  and  generate_-
* FunctionQueryArgs/5 ). To place the actual arguments  return_val,v1,...,vn  at
* the proper positions in the clause head the QueryCompiler needs further infor-
* mations from the ".builtin" file.This information corresponds to a type decla-
* ration of of the clause process_f/n+1 and  is  represented  by  the  following
* fact :
*
*   QueryArgExp(f,[this,p(p1),...,p(pn)]).
*
* The first argument is the function name,the second argument is a list of argu-
* ment specifications of the function. The i-th element of this list corresponds
* to the i-th argument of the clause head process_f(_this,_p1,...,_pn). The  key
* word "this" indicates the return value which can be interpreted as a  computed
* instance of <primitive superclass>, the superclass of f.The term p(pi) denotes
* the parameter attribute pi of f.
*
*
* Further changes were made concerning the compilation of query  classes  having
* computed and/or parameter attributes with primitive  attribute  value  classes
* and/or  queries  with  primitive  superclasses. Consider, e.g., the  following
* frames :
*
*   (1) QueryClass Q isA <primitive class> with
*         ...
*       end Q
*
*   (2) GenericQueryClass GQ isA S1,...,Sk with
*          computed_attribute ,parameter
*              ca : <primitive class>
*          parameter
*              pa : <primitive class>
*          ...
*       end GQ
*
* In case (1) the corresponding PL-tree of Q contains a subtree
*
*              and(lit(InstanceOf(this,<primitive class>,'_')),_t)
*
* When evaluating the generated query rule the corresponding sub goal  prove_li-
* teral(InstanceOf(_this,_<primitive class>,_)) will fail since _this is not in-
* stanciated at this time and _<primitive class> is a primitive class, e.g. Real
* ( see above;there is a new predicate defined,is_primitive_class/1, which tests
* whether a class is a primitive class or not ).
*
* In case (2) the PL-tree of GQ will contain a subtree
*
*    and(lit(InstanceOf(ca,<primitive class>,'_')),
*        and(lit(InstanceOf(ca,p<primitive class>,'_')),
*            _t1)
*       )
*
* and _t1 contains a subtree
*
*    and(lit(InstanceOf(pa,p<primitive class>,'_')),_t2).
*
* The 'p' is prepended to <primitive class> by the query  compiler  to  generate
* new  class  identifiers.These may be instanciated at evaluation time with spe-
* cializations of <primitive class> or with <primitive class>.
*
* For the same reasons as in case (1) the evaluation of the generated query rule
* will fail, too. Thus, these InstanceOf literals must be  lazy  evaluated, i.e,
* when the first argument is instanciated. This  is  accomplished  by  selecting
* those InstanceOf literals in separate "and"-trees which will finally be merged
* together with the original part of the PL-tree. ReorderAnds$LTassertionSimpli-
* fier/2 is therefore reimplemented to preserve  the  ordering  of  subtrees  of
* "and"-trees having these InstanceOf literals as leaves.
*
* In summary, the following predicates are modified or added :
*
*  For replacing derive expressions of functions :
*
*  resolve_derive_expression/2
*  replace_derive_expression/3
*  generate_FunctionQueryArgs/5
*  prove_literal$Literals/1
*
*  For lazy evaluation :
*
*  construct_isa_tree/2
*  construct_with_tree/3
*  conjunct_expression/2
*  construct_cattr_tree/3
*  construct_cattr/5
*  construct_param_tree/3
*  construct_param/5
*  merge_trees/2
*  remove_empty_and_sons/2
*  reorderAnds$LTassertionSimplifier/2
*



